					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Pro=
ducing a sequence that cannot be predicted better than by random chance</di=
v>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Two_red_dice_01.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/3/36/Two_red_dice_01.svg/250px-Two_red_dice_01.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"160" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"671" data-file-height=3D"430"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Dice" title=3D"Dice">Dice</a> are an example of a hardware =
random number generator. When a cubical die is rolled, a random number from=
 1 to 6 is obtained.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Random number generation</b> is a process by which, often by means of=
 a <b>random number generator</b> (<b>RNG</b>), a sequence of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number" title=3D"Number">numbers</a> or <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbol" title=3D"Symbol">symbols</a> is g=
enerated that cannot be reasonably predicted better than by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random">ra=
ndom</a> chance. This means that the particular outcome sequence will conta=
in some patterns detectable in hindsight but impossible to foresee. True ra=
ndom number generators can be <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
ardware_random_number_generator" title=3D"Hardware random number generator"=
>hardware random-number generators</a></i> (HRNGs), wherein each generation=
 is a function of the current value of a physical environment's attribute t=
hat is constantly changing in a manner that is practically impossible to mo=
del. This would be in contrast to so-called <i>random number generations</i=
> done by <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_g=
enerator" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">pseudorandom number gener=
ators</a></i> (PRNGs), which generate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pseudorandom" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudorandom">pseudorandom=
</a> numbers that are in fact predetermined=E2=80=94these numbers can be re=
produced simply by knowing the initial state of the PRNG and the method it =
uses to generate numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-1"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> There is also a class of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
on-physical_true_random_number_generator" title=3D"Non-physical true random=
 number generator">non-physical true random number generators</a> (NPTRNG) =
that produce true random numbers without an access to a dedicated hardware =
source, by scavenging entropy that is present in the computer system.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchindler200818_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-FOOTNOTESch=
indler200818-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> See the details in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#True_vs._pseudo-random_numbers">True v=
s. pseudo-random numbers</a>.
</p><p>Various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applications_of_ran=
domness" title=3D"Applications of randomness">applications of randomness</a=
> have led to the development of different methods for generating <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ra=
ndom">random</a> data. Some of these have existed since ancient times, incl=
uding well-known examples like the rolling of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Dice" title=3D"Dice">dice</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Coin_flipping" title=3D"Coin flipping">coin flipping</a>, the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shuffling" title=3D"Shuffling">shuffli=
ng</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Playing_card" title=3D"P=
laying card">playing cards</a>, the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Yarrow" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Yarrow">yarrow</a> stalks (=
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Ching_divination" title=3D"I=
 Ching divination">divination</a>) in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/I_Ching" title=3D"I Ching">I Ching</a>, as well as countless other =
techniques. Because of the mechanical nature of these techniques, generatin=
g large quantities of sufficiently random numbers (important in statistics)=
 required much work and time. Thus, results would sometimes be collected an=
d distributed as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_tab=
le" title=3D"Random number table">random number tables</a>.
</p><p>Several computational methods for pseudorandom number generation exi=
st. All fall short of the goal of true randomness, although they may meet, =
with varying success, some of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistical_randomness" title=3D"Statistical randomness">statistical tests =
for randomness</a> intended to measure how unpredictable their results are =
(that is, to what degree their patterns are discernible). This generally ma=
kes them unusable for applications such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryptography</a>. However, ca=
refully designed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographically=
_secure_pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Cryptographically secure ps=
eudorandom number generator"><i>cryptographically secure pseudorandom numbe=
r generators</i></a> (CSPRNGS) also exist, with special features specifical=
ly designed for use in cryptography.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Practical_applications_and_=
uses">Practical applications and uses</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Practical applications and uses"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applications_of_randomness" titl=
e=3D"Applications of randomness">Applications of randomness</a></div>
<p>Random number generators have applications in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Gambling" title=3D"Gambling">gambling</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_sampling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Statistical sampling">statistical sampling</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_simulation" title=3D"Computer simulation">comput=
er simulation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" t=
itle=3D"Cryptography">cryptography</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Completely_randomized_design" title=3D"Completely randomized design">=
completely randomized design</a>, and other areas where producing an unpred=
ictable result is desirable.  Generally, in applications having unpredictab=
ility as the paramount feature, such as in security applications, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardware_random_number_generator" title=
=3D"Hardware random number generator">hardware generators</a> are generally=
 preferred over pseudorandom algorithms, where feasible.
</p><p>Pseudorandom number generators are very useful in developing  <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Monte Carlo=
 method">Monte Carlo-method</a> simulations, as <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Debugging" title=3D"Debugging">debugging</a> is facilitated b=
y the ability to run the same sequence of random numbers again by starting =
from the same <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_seed" titl=
e=3D"Random seed">random seed</a></i>. They are also used in cryptography =
=E2=80=93 so long as the <i>seed</i> is secret. The sender and receiver can=
 generate the same set of numbers automatically to use as keys.
</p><p>The generation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudoran=
dom_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudorandom number">pseudorando=
m numbers</a> is an important and common task in computer programming. Whil=
e cryptography and certain numerical algorithms require a very high degree =
of <i>apparent</i> randomness, many other operations only need a modest amo=
unt of unpredictability. Some simple examples might be presenting a user wi=
th a "random quote of the day", or determining which way a computer-control=
led adversary might move in a computer game. Weaker forms of <i>randomness<=
/i> are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_algorithm" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hash algorithm">hash algorithms</a> and in cre=
ating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amortized" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Amortized">amortized</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Search_algorithm" title=3D"Search algorithm">searching</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sorting_algorithm" title=3D"Sorting algor=
ithm">sorting algorithms</a>.
</p><p>Some applications that appear at first sight to be suitable for <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomization" title=3D"Randomization"=
>randomization</a> are in fact not quite so simple. For instance, a system =
that "randomly" selects music tracks for a background music system must onl=
y <i>appear</i> random, and may even have ways to control the selection of =
music: a truly random system would have no restriction on the same item app=
earing two or three times in succession.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"True_vs._pseudo-random_numb=
ers">True vs. pseudo-random numbers</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: True vs. pseudo-random numbers"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number=
_generator" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">Pseudorandom number gen=
erator</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardware_random_num=
ber_generator" title=3D"Hardware random number generator">Hardware random n=
umber generator</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographically_secure=
_pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Cryptographically secure pseudoran=
dom number generator">Cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generato=
r</a></div>
<p>There are two principal methods used to generate random numbers. The fir=
st method measures some physical phenomenon that is expected to be random a=
nd then compensates for possible biases in the measurement process. Example=
 sources include measuring <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosph=
eric_noise" title=3D"Atmospheric noise">atmospheric noise</a>, thermal nois=
e, and other external electromagnetic and quantum phenomena. For example, c=
osmic background radiation or radioactive decay as measured over short time=
scales represent sources of natural <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Entropy_(information_theory)" title=3D"Entropy (information theory)">entr=
opy</a> (as a measure of unpredictability or surprise of the number generat=
ion process).
</p><p>The speed at which entropy can be obtained from natural sources is d=
ependent on the underlying physical phenomena being measured. Thus, sources=
 of naturally occurring <i>true</i> entropy are said to be <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blocking_(computing)" title=3D"Blocking (computing=
)">blocking</a>&nbsp;=E2=80=93  they are rate-limited until enough entropy =
is harvested to meet the demand. On some Unix-like systems, including most =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_distribution" title=3D"Linux=
 distribution">Linux distributions</a>, the pseudo device file <span class=
=3D"monospaced"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki//dev/random" title=
=3D"/dev/random">/dev/random</a></span> will block until sufficient entropy=
 is harvested from the environment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_n=
ote-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Due to this blocking behavior, large bulk reads from <lin=
k rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r8860=
49734"><span class=3D"monospaced">/dev/random</span>, such as filling a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_disk_drive" title=3D"Hard disk d=
rive">hard disk drive</a> with random bits, can often be slow on systems th=
at use this type of entropy source.
</p><p>The second method uses computational <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> that can produce lo=
ng sequences of apparently random results, which are in fact completely det=
ermined by a shorter initial value, known as a seed value or <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_(cryptography)" title=3D"Key (cryptography)"=
>key</a>. As a result, the entire seemingly random sequence can be reproduc=
ed if the seed value is known. This type of random number generator is ofte=
n called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_gen=
erator" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">pseudorandom number generat=
or</a>. This type of generator typically does not rely on sources of natura=
lly occurring entropy, though it may be periodically seeded by natural sour=
ces. This generator type is non-blocking, so they are not rate-limited by a=
n external event, making large bulk reads a possibility.
</p><p>Standard cryptographic designs take a hybrid approach, using randomn=
ess harvested from natural sources to seed a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cryptographically_secure_pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D=
"Cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator">cryptographically =
secure pseudorandom number generators</a> (CSPRNGs). Hardware random number=
 generators generally produce only a limited number of random bits per seco=
nd. In order to increase the available output data rate, they are often use=
d to generate the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_seed" ti=
tle=3D"Random seed">seed</a>" for a faster PRNG. PRNG also helps with the n=
oise source "anonymization" (whitening out the noise source identifying cha=
racteristics) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomness_extra=
ctor" title=3D"Randomness extractor">entropy extraction</a>. With a proper =
PRNG algorithm selected (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptogra=
phically_secure_pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Cryptographically s=
ecure pseudorandom number generator">cryptographically secure pseudorandom =
number generator</a>, CSPRNG), the combination can satisfy the requirements=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing=
_Standards" title=3D"Federal Information Processing Standards">Federal Info=
rmation Processing Standards</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Common_Criteria" title=3D"Common Criteria">Common Criteria</a> standards=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESaarinenNewellMarshall2020_4-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cit=
e_note-FOOTNOTESaarinenNewellMarshall2020-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generation_methods">Generat=
ion methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Random_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Generation methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Physical_methods">Physical =
methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRand=
om_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Physical methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardware_random_numb=
er_generator" title=3D"Hardware random number generator">Hardware random nu=
mber generator</a></div>
<p>The earliest methods for generating random numbers, such as dice, coin f=
lipping and roulette wheels, are still used today, mainly in games and gamb=
ling, as they tend to be too slow for most applications in statistics and c=
ryptography.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardware_random_number_ge=
nerator" title=3D"Hardware random number generator">hardware random number =
generator</a> can be based on an essentially random atomic or subatomic phy=
sical phenomenon whose unpredictability can be traced to the laws of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mech=
anics">quantum mechanics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-5"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Source=
s of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(information_theory)"=
 title=3D"Entropy (information theory)">entropy</a> include <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactive_decay" title=3D"Radioactive decay">ra=
dioactive decay</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_noise=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Thermal noise">thermal noise</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shot_noise" title=3D"Shot noise">shot noi=
se</a>, avalanche noise in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zener_d=
iode" title=3D"Zener diode">Zener diodes</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Clock_drift#Random_number_generators" title=3D"Clock drift">clo=
ck drift</a>, the timing of actual movements of a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Hard_disk" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hard disk">hard d=
isk</a> read-write head, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio=
_noise" title=3D"Radio noise">radio noise</a>.  However, physical phenomena=
 and tools used to measure them generally feature asymmetries and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systematic_bias" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Systematic bias">systematic biases</a> that make their outcomes not =
uniformly random.  A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomness_ex=
tractor" title=3D"Randomness extractor">randomness extractor</a>, such as a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_hash_function" titl=
e=3D"Cryptographic hash function">cryptographic hash function</a>, can be u=
sed to approach a uniform distribution of bits from a non-uniformly random =
source, though at a lower bit rate.
</p><p>The appearance of wideband photonic entropy sources, such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optical_chaos" title=3D"Optical chaos">op=
tical chaos</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplified_spon=
taneous_emission" title=3D"Amplified spontaneous emission">amplified sponta=
neous emission</a> noise, greatly aid the development of the physical rando=
m number generator. Among them, optical chaos<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_gener=
ation#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-8"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> has a high potential to physically produce high-speed random nu=
mbers due to its high bandwidth and large amplitude. A prototype of a high-=
speed, real-time physical random bit generator based on a chaotic laser was=
 built in 2013.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-9"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Various imaginative ways of collecting this entropic information hav=
e been devised. One technique is to run a hash function against a frame of =
a video stream from an unpredictable source. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Lavarand" title=3D"Lavarand">Lavarand</a> used this technique wi=
th images of a number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lava_lamp=
" title=3D"Lava lamp">lava lamps</a>. <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external=
 text" href=3D"http://www.fourmilab.ch/hotbits/">HotBits</a> measured radio=
active decay with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geiger%E2%80%93M=
uller_tube" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geiger=E2=80=93Muller tube">Geig=
er=E2=80=93Muller tubes</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-10=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> while <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random.org" ti=
tle=3D"Random.org">Random.org</a> uses variations in the amplitude of atmos=
pheric noise recorded with a normal radio.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/79/Demo_random_SMIL.svg"><img r=
esource=3D"/wiki/File:Demo_random_SMIL.svg" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia=
.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Demo_random_SMIL.svg/250px-Demo_random_SM=
IL.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"190" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"512"></a><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Demo_random_SMIL.svg" class=3D"mw-file-m=
agnify"></a><figcaption>Demonstration of a simple random number generator b=
ased on where and when a button is clicked</figcaption></figure>
<p>Another common entropy source is the behavior of human users of the syst=
em. While people are not considered good randomness generators upon request=
, they generate random behavior quite well in the context of playing <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mixed_strategy" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Mixed strategy">mixed strategy</a> games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_gen=
eration#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some security-related computer software r=
equires the user to make a lengthy series of mouse movements or keyboard in=
puts to create sufficient entropy needed to generate random <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_(cryptography)" title=3D"Key (cryptography)">=
keys</a> or to initialize pseudorandom number generators.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_n=
umber_generation#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_methods">Comp=
utational methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"=
Edit section: Computational methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
