<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_=
generation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generation">=
Pseudorandom number generation</a></div>
<p>Most computer-generated random numbers use PRNGs which are algorithms th=
at can automatically create long runs of numbers with good random propertie=
s but eventually the sequence repeats (or the memory usage grows without bo=
und). These random numbers are fine in many situations but are not as rando=
m as numbers generated from electromagnetic atmospheric noise used as a sou=
rce of entropy.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2025)">citation nee=
ded</span></a></i>]</sup> The series of values generated by such algorithms=
 is generally determined by a fixed number called a <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_seed" title=3D"Random seed">seed</a></i>. One o=
f the most common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_num=
ber_generator" title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">PRNG</a> is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_congruential_generator" title=
=3D"Linear congruential generator">linear congruential generator</a>, which=
 uses the recurrence
</p>
