        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>mod</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>m</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X_{n+1}=3D(aX=
_{n}+b)\,{\textrm {mod}}\,m}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4595ec3472446db9f4a7e19f5902191034a91744" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:25.567ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X_=
{n+1}=3D(aX_{n}+b)\,{\textrm {mod}}\,m}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>to generate numbers, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">b</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">m</span> are large integers, and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math=
-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y=
" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM=
L" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle X_{n+1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X_{n+1}}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4a5e2ebcd9ef3ffc3f45a5745884e0a46de672cf" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:5.243ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X_{=
n+1}}"></span> is the next in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">X</span> as a series of pseudorandom numbers. The maximum numb=
er of numbers the formula can produce is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modulus_(algebraic_number_theory)" title=3D"Modulus (algebraic n=
umber theory)">modulus</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">m</span>. The recurrence relation can be extended to matrices to=
 have much longer periods and better statistical properties.
</p><p>To avoid certain non-random properties of a single linear congruenti=
al generator, several such random number generators with slightly different=
 values of the multiplier coefficient, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, can be used in parallel, with a <i>master=
</i> random number generator that selects from among the several different =
generators.
</p><p>A simple pen-and-paper method for generating random numbers is the s=
o-called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-square_method" tit=
le=3D"Middle-square method">middle-square method</a> suggested by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neuma=
nn">John von Neumann</a>. While simple to implement, its output is of poor =
quality. It has a very short period and severe weaknesses, such as the outp=
ut sequence almost always converging to zero.  A recent innovation is to co=
mbine the middle square with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wey=
l_sequence" title=3D"Weyl sequence">Weyl sequence</a>. This method produces=
 high-quality output through a long period.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generati=
on#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Most computer programming languages include functions or library rou=
tines that provide random number generators. They are often designed to pro=
vide a random byte or word, or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
loating_point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Floating point">floating poin=
t</a> number <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_distribution_=
(continuous)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform distribution (continuo=
us)">uniformly distributed</a> between 0 and 1.
</p><p>The quality i.e. randomness of such library functions varies widely =
from completely predictable output to cryptographically secure. The default=
 random number generator in many languages, including Python, Ruby, R, IDL =
and PHP is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_T=
wister" title=3D"Mersenne Twister">Mersenne Twister</a> algorithm and is <i=
>not</i> sufficient for cryptography purposes, as is explicitly stated in t=
he language documentation. Such library functions often have poor statistic=
al properties, and some will repeat patterns after only tens of thousands o=
f trials.  They are often initialized using a computer's <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-time_clock" title=3D"Real-time clock">real-time=
 clock</a> as the seed, since such a clock is 64 bits and measures in nanos=
econds, far beyond the person's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ac=
curacy_and_precision" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">precision</a>. These=
 functions may provide enough randomness for certain tasks (for example, vi=
deo games) but are unsuitable where high-quality randomness is required, su=
ch as in cryptography applications or statistics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_ge=
neration#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Much higher quality random number sources are available on most oper=
ating systems; for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki//dev/r=
andom" title=3D"/dev/random">/dev/random</a> on various BSD flavors, Linux,=
 Mac OS X, IRIX, and Solaris, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ryptGenRandom" title=3D"CryptGenRandom">CryptGenRandom</a> for Microsoft Wi=
ndows. Most programming languages, including those mentioned above, provide=
 a means to access these higher-quality sources.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"By_humans">By humans</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_gene=
ration&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: By humans"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>Random number generation may also be performed by humans, in the form of=
 collecting various inputs from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/En=
d_user" title=3D"End user">end users</a> and using them as a randomization =
source. However, most studies find that human subjects have some degree of =
non-randomness when attempting to produce a random sequence of e.g., digits=
 or letters.  They may alternate too much between choices when compared to =
a good random generator;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-15"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> thus, this approach is not widely used. However, for the very rea=
son that humans perform poorly in this task, human random number generation=
 can be used as a tool to gain insights into brain functions otherwise not =
accessible.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Post-processing_and_statist=
ical_checks">Post-processing and statistical checks</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Post-processing and statist=
ical checks"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomness_tests" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Randomness tests">Randomness tests</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_randomness" title=3D"Statisti=
cal randomness">Statistical randomness</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/List_of_random_number_generators" title=3D"List of random num=
ber generators">List of random number generators</a></div>
<p>Even given a source of plausible random numbers (perhaps from a quantum =
mechanically based hardware generator), obtaining numbers which are complet=
ely unbiased takes care. In addition, behavior of these generators often ch=
anges with temperature, power supply voltage, the age of the device, or oth=
er outside interference.
</p><p>Generated random numbers are sometimes subjected to statistical test=
s before use to ensure that the underlying source is still working, and the=
n post-processed to improve their statistical properties. An example would =
be the TRNG9803<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 hardware random number generator, which uses an entropy measurement as a h=
ardware test, and then post-processes the random sequence with a shift regi=
ster stream cipher. It is generally hard to use statistical tests to valida=
te the generated random numbers. Wang and Nicol<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_gene=
ration#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> proposed a distance-based statistical test=
ing technique that is used to identify the weaknesses of several random gen=
erators. Li and Wang<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-19"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> proposed a method of testing random numbers based on laser chaotic en=
tropy sources using Brownian motion properties.
</p><p>Statistical tests are also used to give confidence that the post-pro=
cessed final output from a random number generator is truly unbiased, with =
numerous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomness_test" title=3D=
"Randomness test">randomness test</a> suites being developed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_considerations">Other=
 considerations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Other considerations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Reshaping_the_distribution"=
>Reshaping the distribution</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9=
" title=3D"Edit section: Reshaping the distribution"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Uniform_distributions">Unif=
orm distributions</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D=
"Edit section: Uniform distributions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Most random number generators natively work with integers or individual =
bits, so an extra step is required to arrive at the <i>canonical</i> unifor=
m distribution between 0 and 1. The implementation is not as trivial as div=
iding the integer by its maximum possible value. Specifically:<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ran=
dom_number_generation#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_gene=
ration#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ol><li>The integer used in the transformation must provide enough bits for=
 the intended precision.</li>
<li>The nature of floating-point math itself means there exists more precis=
ion the closer the number is to zero. This extra precision is usually not u=
sed due to the sheer number of bits required.</li>
<li>Rounding error in division may bias the result. At worst, a supposedly =
excluded bound may be drawn contrary to expectations based on real-number m=
ath.</li></ol>
<p>The mainstream algorithm, used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/OpenJDK" title=3D"OpenJDK">OpenJDK</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rust_(programming_language)" title=3D"Rust (programming language)"=
>Rust</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NumPy" title=3D"Num=
Py">NumPy</a>, is described in a proposal for <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B" title=3D"C++">C++</a>'s STL. It does not use the extra=
 precision and suffers from bias only in the last bit due to round-to-even.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other numeric =
concerns are warranted when shifting this <i>canonical</i> uniform distribu=
tion to a different range.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-23">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> A proposed method for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Swift_programming_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Swift progra=
mming language">Swift programming language</a> claims to use the full preci=
sion everywhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-24"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Uniformly distributed integers are commonly used in algorithms such =
as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%E2%80%93Yates_shuffl=
e" title=3D"Fisher=E2=80=93Yates shuffle">Fisher=E2=80=93Yates shuffle</a>.=
 Again, a naive implementation may induce a modulo bias into the result, so=
 more involved algorithms must be used. A method that nearly never performs=
 division was described in 2018 by Daniel Lemire,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_ge=
neration#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> with the current state-of-the-art bein=
g the arithmetic encoding-inspired 2021 "optimal algorithm" by Stephen Cano=
n of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple_Inc." title=3D"Apple In=
c.">Apple Inc.</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-26"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Most 0 to 1 RNGs include 0 but exclude 1, while others include or ex=
clude both.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Other_distributions">Other =
distributions</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Other distributions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-random_number=
_sampling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudo-random number sampling">Ps=
eudo-random number sampling</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulative_distribution_=
function" title=3D"Cumulative distribution function">cumulative distributio=
n function</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantile_functi=
on" title=3D"Quantile function">quantile function</a></div>
<p>Given a source of uniform random numbers, there are a couple of methods =
to create a new random source that corresponds to a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function" title=3D"Probability densit=
y function">probability density function</a>. One method called the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inversion_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Inversion method">inversion method</a>, involves integrating up to =
an area greater than or equal to the random number (which should be generat=
ed between 0 and 1 for proper distributions). A second method called the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceptance-rejection_method" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Acceptance-rejection method">acceptance-rejection=
 method</a>, involves choosing an x and y value and testing whether the fun=
ction of x is greater than the y value.  If it is, the x value is accepted.=
  Otherwise, the x value is rejected and the algorithm tries again.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-28=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_numbe=
r_generation#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As an example for rejection sampling, to generate a pair of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistically_independent" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Statistically independent">statistically independent</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Norma=
l distribution">standard normally distributed</a> random numbers (<i>x</i>,=
 <i>y</i>), one may first generate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Polar_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polar coordinates">p=
olar coordinates</a> (<i>r</i>, <i>=CE=B8</i>), where <i>r</i><sup>2</sup>~=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution" title=3D=
"Chi-squared distribution">=CF=87<sub>2</sub><sup>2</sup></a> and <i>=CE=B8=
</i>~<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_distribution_(continu=
ous)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform distribution (continuous)">UNI=
FORM(0,2=CF=80)</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box%E2%80=
%93Muller_transform" title=3D"Box=E2=80=93Muller transform">Box=E2=80=93Mul=
ler transform</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Whitening">Whitening</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_gene=
ration&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Whitening=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>The outputs of multiple independent RNGs can be combined (for example, u=
sing a bit-wise <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XOR" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"XOR">XOR</a> operation) to provide a combined RNG at leas=
t as good as the best RNG used. This is referred to as <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_whitening" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sof=
tware whitening">software whitening</a>.
</p><p>Computational and hardware random number generators are sometimes co=
mbined to reflect the benefits of both kinds. Computational random number g=
enerators can typically generate pseudorandom numbers much faster than phys=
ical generators, while physical generators can generate true randomness.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Low-discrepancy_sequences_a=
s_an_alternative">Low-discrepancy sequences as an alternative</h2><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Low-discrepancy =
sequences as an alternative"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some computations making use of a random number generator can be summari=
zed as the computation of a total or average value, such as the computation=
 of integrals by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_m=
ethod" title=3D"Monte Carlo method">Monte Carlo method</a>. For such proble=
ms, it may be possible to find a more accurate solution by the use of so-ca=
lled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-discrepancy_sequence" tit=
le=3D"Low-discrepancy sequence">low-discrepancy sequences</a>, also called =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasirandom" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Quasirandom">quasirandom</a> numbers. Such sequences have a defin=
ite pattern that fills in gaps evenly, qualitatively speaking; a truly rand=
om sequence may, and usually does, leave larger gaps.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Activities_and_demonstratio=
ns">Activities and demonstrations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_generation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Activities and demonstrations"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The following sites make available random number samples:
</p>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOCR" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"SOCR">SOCR</a> resource pages contain a number of hands-on i=
nteractive activities and demonstrations of random number generation using =
Java applets.</li>
<li>The Quantum Optics Group at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/ANU" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ANU">ANU</a> generates random numbers=
 sourced from quantum vacuum. Samples of random numbers are available at th=
eir quantum random number generator research page.</li>
<li>Random.org makes available random numbers that are sourced from the ran=
domness of atmospheric noise.</li>
<li>The Quantum Random Bit Generator Service at the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ru%C4%91er_Bo%C5%A1kovi%C4%87_Institute" title=3D"Ru=C4=
=91er Bo=C5=A1kovi=C4=87 Institute">Ru=C4=91er Bo=C5=A1kovi=C4=87 Institute=
</a> harvests randomness from the quantum process of photonic emission in s=
emiconductors. They supply a variety of ways of fetching the data, includin=
g libraries for several programming languages.</li>
<li>The Group at the Taiyuan University of Technology generates random numb=
ers sourced from a chaotic laser. Samples of random numbers are available a=
t their physical random number generator service.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Backdoors">Backdoors</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRandom_number_gene=
ration&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Backdoors=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_genera=
tor_attack" title=3D"Random number generator attack">Random number generato=
r attack</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backdoor_(com=
puting)" title=3D"Backdoor (computing)">Backdoor (computing)</a></div>
<p>Since much cryptography depends on a cryptographically secure random num=
ber generator for key and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptogr=
aphic_nonce" title=3D"Cryptographic nonce">cryptographic nonce</a> generati=
on, if a random number generator can be made predictable, it can be used as=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backdoor_(computing)" title=3D"Ba=
ckdoor (computing)">backdoor</a> by an attacker to break the encryption.
</p><p>The NSA is reported to have inserted a backdoor into the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIST" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NIST">NI=
ST</a> certified <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographically=
_secure_pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Cryptographically secure ps=
eudorandom number generator">cryptographically secure pseudorandom number g=
enerator</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_EC_DRBG" title=
=3D"Dual EC DRBG">Dual EC DRBG</a>. If for example an SSL connection is cre=
ated using this random number generator, then according to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Green_(cryptographer)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Matthew Green (cryptographer)">Matthew Green</a> it would allow=
 NSA to determine the state of the random number generator, and thereby eve=
ntually be able to read all data sent over the SSL connection.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ran=
dom_number_generation#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Even though it was apparent=
 that Dual_EC_DRBG was a very poor and possibly backdoored pseudorandom num=
ber generator long before the NSA backdoor was confirmed in 2013, it had se=
en significant usage in practice until 2013, for example by the prominent s=
ecurity company <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Security" titl=
e=3D"RSA Security">RSA Security</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-green_30-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_gener=
ation#cite_note-green-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There have subsequently been accusati=
ons that RSA Security knowingly inserted a NSA backdoor into its products, =
possibly as part of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullrun_pr=
ogram" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bullrun program">Bullrun program</a>.=
 RSA has denied knowingly inserting a backdoor into its products.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Random_number_generation#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It has also been theorized that hardware RNGs could be secretly modi=
fied to have less entropy than stated, which would make encryption using th=
e hardware RNG susceptible to attack. One such method that has been publish=
ed works by modifying the dopant mask of the chip, which would be undetecta=
ble to optical reverse-engineering.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_=
note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> For example, for random number generation in Linux, it=
 is seen as unacceptable to use Intel's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/RDRAND" title=3D"RDRAND">RDRAND</a> hardware RNG without mixing in th=
e RDRAND output with other sources of entropy to counteract any backdoors i=
n the hardware RNG, especially after the revelation of the NSA Bullrun prog=
ram.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
andom_number_generation#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2010, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hot_Lotto_fraud_sc=
andal" title=3D"Hot Lotto fraud scandal">a U.S. lottery draw was rigged</a>=
 by the information security director of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Multi-State_Lottery_Association" title=3D"Multi-State Lottery As=
sociation">Multi-State Lottery Association</a> (MUSL), who surreptitiously =
installed backdoor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malware" title=
=3D"Malware">malware</a> on the MUSL's secure RNG computer during routine m=
aintenance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dailybeast-hotlotto_35-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation#cite_no=
te-dailybeast-hotlotto-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> During the hacks the man won a total=
 amount of $16,500,000 over multiple years.
</p>
